defaultWritten evidence submitted by Novamont, the Kyoto Club, The Italian Association of defaultBioplasticsdefault and the Italian Composting Association default&#xa0;default1.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe are a group of Italian organisations looking to provide the Committee with information on the effect of a ban on single use-plastic bags in Italy (with exemptions for dual-use compostable bags).
default&#xa0;
default1.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe measure has had a number of benefits for the re-industrialisation of the European and Italian chemical sector, as well as benefits to organic recycling and agricultural industries and the Italian Environment.
default&#xa0;
default1.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe policy measure has helped the support emergence of a 
defaultbioplastics
default industry (plastics made from starch and vegetable oils) at a time when its traditional chemical industry is faltering. This sector is far less reliant on petrochemicals.
default&#xa0;
default1.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe introduction of compostable bags has increased the level and quality of organic recycling – which has been beneficial to both the farming and 
defaultbiowaste
default industries. It has also reduced the costs of disposal (landfill and incineration) for local Government.
default&#xa0;
default1.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere has been a decline in the volume of plastic litter in the marine environment.
default&#xa0;
