default&#xa0;
default3.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA circular economy is one that which requires that energy come from renewable resources and that biological materials, such as food waste, are returned to the organic and economic cycles.
default&#xa0;
default3.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe law was aimed at reducing the environmental contamination caused by traditional plastic bags. With this in mind, and to help support the Italian 
defaultbioplastics
default industry, an exemption was allowed for compostable bags.
default&#xa0;
default3.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSince its introduction, the new law has helped reduce the consumption of carrier bags by 33% (from 145kton 2010 to 97kton in 2012). In 2011, Italian producers of films and biodegradable compostable bags i
defaultncreased their workforce 
defaultand through investment in research and new machinery a further 500 jobs were created (according to Plastic Consult).
defaultThis level of investment would not have been made possible without the policy certainty created by the new law.
default&#xa0;
default3.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOne un
defaultintended 
defaultconsequence of the law was the exploitation of legislative loopholes – namely the lack of a clear requirement to comply with the European Norm for compostable plastics (EN13432:200
default0
default). 
defaultAs such there has been a proliferation of plastic bags claiming to be biodegradable; these products gained their biodegradable status because of weak certification processes and a system of self-declarations. 
defaultThis loophole was closed in 2013 with the introduction of a new law and fiscal penalties, but this serves to prove the need for any exemptions to be specific with penalties for breaches.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default4.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultItaly’s tourism industry is dependent on a clean marine environment. Single use plastic bags make up the majority 
defaultof pollution in the marine environment. As such, action had to be taken by the Italian Government. 
defaultDegradable bags offer a potential solution to the problem of build up of plastic waste in the sea. The paragraphs below explain in more detail.
default&#xa0;
default4.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWith more than 8,000 km of coastline, Italy is badly 
defaultaffected
default by plastic litter in the marine environment – particularly as any deterioration in the environment impacts tourism - a fundamental economic resource for the country. 
default&#xa0;
default4.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn March 2011, the Environmental Protection Agencies of Tuscany and Emilia Romagna carried out an environmental survey which revealed that 73% of human-origin waste found on the seabed is made up of plastic bags of various sizes. Further monitoring has revealed that 95% of the large-scale refuse floating in the Tyrrhenian Sea is made up of plastic, 41% of this being made up of plastic bags and fragments.
default&#xa0;
default4.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultConventional plastics are strongly resistant to biodegradation, and tend to build up in the marine environment if not properly disposed of. Moreover many studies show that, in the long term, plastic bags are transformed in small fragments of dimension and concentration similar to plankton with the risk of entering in the food chain. 
default&#xa0;
default4.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe European Standard, EN13432:200
default0
default, used to determine biodegradation of packaging items was established to verify biodegradation for composting 
defaultpurposes. 
defaultIn 2012, an Italian study investigated biodegradation in different marine habitats and the tests indicated that the EN13432:200
default0
default compostable films biodegraded to a substantial extent (88% in 236 days) in conditions replicating the sea bed and had completely disappeared on the shoreline tests. These results mirrored those of Plymouth University who found that compostable bags fully degraded (disappeared completely) in 24 weeks in Queens Anne Battery Marina unlike the conventional or pro-oxidant (
defaultoxo
default-degradable) polythene which showed almost no change (max 2%) in 40 weeks.
default&#xa0;
default4.6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultStudies as to how the measure has affected waste going into the marine environment are ongoing.
