default5.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Italian chemicals industry – due 
defaultin part 
defaultto high feedstock costs has been in long term decline. The emergence of a 
defaultbioplastics
default industry – underpinned by a legal system which supports the development of 
defaultbioplastics
default has played a role in reversing this decline, and reduced the fossil fuel dependence of the industry. See below for detail.
default&#xa0;
default5.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFrom the 1930s until the 1990s, Italy was one of the world’s leading research and manufacturing hubs for plastics. 
defaultIn addition, up 
defaultuntil 2012
default, Italy was (
defaultper capita
default)
default Europe’s largest consumer of flexible plastic packaging and in particular carrier bags.
default&#xa0;
default5.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHowever, the combination of overexpansion, increased competition from cheaper imports and a lack of enforced regulation over 
defaulttime
default meant that Italy’s global position in the traditional chemical market declined significantly. 
default&#xa0;
default5.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDuring the 
defaulte
defaultconomic crisis of 2009, the fragility of the industry was further exposed and multinational chemical companies across the country were forced to close their older facilities. The industrial crisis was compounded further by the relative cost of naphtha (€761 / tonne in Italy v €93 / tonne in the Middle East) meaning the traditional plastics industry was increasingly concentrated outside of Italy and Europe and into Asia
default...
default 
default&#xa0;
default5.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultConsequently, Italy went from being a leader in manufacturing and exports to being a net importer (7% of internal production against 19% imports). A situation not dissimilar to that of the UK.
