default6.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSince 1992 the most common tools for collecting food waste in Italy are a small cont
defaultainer (7 – 10l
default) and compostable liners for use in the kitchen and a larger outdoor container (25l) which is emptied twice a week. Following a visit by WRAP to Novamont and northern Italy in 2006, this system of collecting food waste has become increasingly common in the UK with over ten million households receiving a food waste collection where compostable liners are accepted.
default&#xa0;
default6.6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSimply collecting materials is half the battle – t
defaulthe importance of quality 
defaultof 
defaultfeedstock
default for efficient organic recycling cannot be over stated. 
defaultThe presence of components that are not completely degradable in a composting feedstock poses a significant risk to the environment. 
defaultIn order to meet the defined quality standards for composted materials the organic recycling industry has to extract the non-biodegradable fraction. Despite the best efforts of local authority collection services, the quantity of non-biodegradable contaminants in 
defaultfeedstock
default presented for organic recycling in Italy and the UK is a serious concern. 
default&#xa0;
default6.7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOver the past decade, substantial data has been collected which supports the need to implement separate collection of bio-waste (including kitchen, agriculture and green waste) to recover valuable resources for soil enhancement while decreasing GHG emissions. Separate collection of municipal as well as commercial bio-waste as the steering principle in bio-waste recycling via composting or anaerobic digestion would constitute the highest level of environmental benefit as well as economic viability. 
default&#xa0;
default6.8.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn Italy, the CIC have calculated that at least 53,000 T of non-compostable plastics have to be removed and sent for disposal each year at a cost of €10-12M. In England, according to the median data of the WRAP ASORI survey for 2012, the quantity of non-compostable plastic is in the region of 64,000T costing the industry at least £15M / year (based on data from the REA).  To put this in context, the latest RECOUP survey shows that less than 7,000T of household plastic film was collected for recycling in 2012. 
default&#xa0;
default6.9.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA study released by CIC has found that impurities in biodegradable waste streams have decreased by 8% and as a result compost is less contaminated by plastic waste. 
defaultThis has happened because the public recognise compostable carrier bags as an equivalent to a caddy liner bag for collection organic waste. Compostable carrier bags now represent a strategic tool to implement high performing organic waste collection schemes and are strongly supported by the CIC and by the Italian Association of the Local Authorities (ANCI)
default.
default&#xa0;
