default&#xa0;default8.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDirective 94/62/EC on Packaging and Packaging Waste defines organic recycling as “the aerobic (composting) or anaerobic (
defaultbiomethanization
default) treatment, under controlled conditions and using micro-organisms, of the biodegradable parts of packaging waste, which produces stabilized organic residues or methane”.  
default&#xa0;
default8.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOver the past decade, substantial data were collected supporting the need to implement separate collection of bio-waste (including kitchen, agriculture and green waste) to recover valuable resources for soil enhancement while decreasing GHG emissions. Separate collection of municipal as well as commercial bio-waste as the steering principle in bio-waste recycling via composting or anaerobic digestion would constitute the highest level of environmental benefit as well as economic viability.
default&#xa0;default8.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSince the introduction of the Italian law, the EU has moved to introduce measures to restrict the consumption of single use plastic bags across the EU. On November 27, the 
defaultEuropean Parliament Environment Committee voted on a number of amendments to the European Strategy on Plastic Waste in the Environment including:
default&#xa0;default8.3.1.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultt
defaulthat the most dangerous plastics, those that by scientific evidence are shown to be the most disruptive to human health and the environment (such as micro- and 
defaultoxo
default‐biodegradable plastics) and those which contain heavy metals and other substances that can also make recycling processes more difficult, should be phased out of the market or banned outright, as soon as possible before 2020
default.
default&#xa0;default8.3.2.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultsingle-use, non-recyclable, non-biodegradable and non-compostable plastic bags should be radically reduced and where possible phased out
